  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM refers to the anxiety and self-doubt that individuals from groups stereotyped as underrepresented in science and technology experience when they are reminded of those stereotypes. As a retired man from Bari, Italy, who held a master's degree and witnessed the educational landscape change over decades, I've seen how this phenomenon can undermine the potential of young minds. In my time, when I was teaching, I noticed that students from certain backgrounds would hesitate to participate in discussions or even attempt complex problems because they feared their efforts would confirm negative stereotypes about their group. This is not just a theoretical issue—it's a lived reality that affects the quality of education and the diversity of ideas in STEM fields. We absolutely must address it, but the approach must be thoughtful and rooted in respect for all individuals. One effective strategy is to create inclusive classrooms where every student's contributions are valued equally, regardless of their background. Additionally, mentoring programs that pair underrepresented students with role models who have successfully navigated STEM careers can help build confidence and counteract the fear of failure. I've also seen the importance of addressing stereotypes directly through open dialogues, not just in academic settings but in community spaces as well. It's crucial to foster an environment where students feel safe to ask questions and make mistakes, knowing that their worth isn't tied to their performance in a single subject. In my own life, I've learned that kindness and patience are the most powerful tools for change. By combining practical support with a deep understanding of the psychological impact of stereotypes, we can create a more equitable and innovative future in STEM.",
